goals.question: What is the trend of unemployment rate over the years?
goals.visualization: Line chart of unemployment rate against year
goals.rationale: This visualization will help to identify if there is any trend in the unemployment rate over the years. It will also help to identify if there are any spikes or dips in the rate.

goals.question: What is the distribution of unemployment rate across different states?
goals.visualization: Bar chart of unemployment rate against state
goals.rationale: This visualization will help to identify which states have higher or lower unemployment rates. It will also help to identify if there are any outliers in the data.

goals.question: What is the relationship between unemployment rate and education level?
goals.visualization: Scatter plot of unemployment rate against education level
goals.rationale: This visualization will help to identify if there is any correlation between education level and unemployment rate. It will also help to identify if there are any outliers in the data.

goals.question: What is the distribution of unemployment rate across different industries?
goals.visualization: Bar chart of unemployment rate against industry
goals.rationale: This visualization will help to identify which industries have higher or lower unemployment rates. It will also help to identify if there are any outliers in the data.

goals.question: What is the trend of unemployment rate for different age groups?
goals.visualization: Line chart of unemployment rate against age group
goals.rationale: This visualization will help to identify if there is any trend in the unemployment rate for different age groups. It will also help to identify if there are any spikes or dips in the rate.

```
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['Year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['Year'], format='%Y')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['Unemployment_Rate'])]
    sns.set_style("whitegrid")
    ax = sns.lineplot(x="Year", y="Unemployment_Rate", data=data, color='blue')
    ax.set(xlabel='Year', ylabel='Unemployment Rate')
    plt.title('What is the trend of unemployment rate over the years?', wrap=True)
    return plt

chart = plot(data)
```

```
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    sns.set(style="whitegrid")
    ax = sns.barplot(x="State", y="Unemployment_Rate", data=data, palette="Blues_d")
    ax.axhline(y=data['Unemployment_Rate'].median(), color='r', linestyle='--', label='Median Unemployment Rate: {:.2f}'.format(data['Unemployment_Rate'].median()))
    ax.set_xticklabels(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=90)
    ax.set(xlabel='State', ylabel='Unemployment Rate')
    ax.legend()
    return plt

chart = plot(data)
```

```
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    sns.set(style="whitegrid")
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))
    sns.barplot(x="industry", y="unemployment_rate", data=data, ax=ax, palette="Blues_d")
    plt.title("What is the distribution of unemployment rate across different industries?", wrap=True)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
    plt.xlabel("Industry")
    plt.ylabel("Unemployment Rate")
    plt.tight_layout()
    return plt

data = pd.read_csv('unemployment.tsv', delimiter='\t')
chart = plot(data)
```

```
    chart = sns.lineplot(x="age_group", y="unemployment_rate", data=data, color='blue')

    plt.title('What is the trend of unemployment rate for different age groups?', wrap=True)
    return plt

data = pd.read_csv('unemployment.tsv', delimiter='\t')
chart = plot(data)
plt.show()
```
